pic','2013-04-10 03:01:14',3,0),('E0-001-055241767-4@2013050414',1,'V0-001-000535977-9','The Musettes','<b>Location:</b> Nampa Civic Center Auditorium<br>  Bring your family along as the Musettes family takes you on a &quot;Sentimental Journey&quot; around the U.S. We will be joined by the Fehrs family fiddlers, the Boise Chordsmen Quartet, and our scholarship winners. This is the very best kind of road trip!<br>','','Adult: $9.00 Student or Senior: $7.00 Children under 12: Free','2013-05-04 14:00:00',NULL,'2013-03-16 21:40:22','2013-03-23 13:25:02','evdb','http://eventful.com/nampa/events/musettes-/E0-001-055241767-4@2013050414?utm_source=apis&utm_medium=apim&utm_campaign=apic','2013-04-10 03:00:26',3,0),('E0-001-055241779-9',1,'V0-001-000535977-9','Mayor\'s Community Prayer Breakfast','<b>Location:</b> Nampa Civic Center Banquet Rooms<br>  Join Mayor Tom Dale, the Liberty/Legacy RAD Choir, and keynote speaker Hugh Friberg at the Mayor&#39;s annual Prayer Breakfast.<br><br> Hugh and Evelyn Friberg spent most of their adult lives serving as career missionaries with the Church of the Nazarene General Board of World Missions in southeast and southern Africa. Hugh served as a pastor among Portuguese-speaking residents of Maputo, (People&#39;s Republic of) Mozambique, for nearly four years. Four years as lead editor of Nazarene publications for Africa Region while living in Johannesburg, Republic of South Africa, during the latter apartheid years, were very formative in ministry in a complex multi-cultural context. Four more years were spent in Johannesburg teaching South African student-pastors, along with twenty-one years in the Kingdom of Swaziland at Nazarene College of Theology. Working with developing national staff and instructing fantastic pastor-students brought a great sense of ministry convergence. Several of those years in Swaziland were spent in ministry among refugees from East Africa and in an inter-denominational and international Christian fellowship in a nearby agricultural community. Now retired and living in Nampa, Idaho, the Fribergs are enjoying ministry in their home church and in Perspectives. Their greatest ministry, however, is helping guide four wonderful grandchildren to maturity! Want to see their pictures?<br><br> Autobiography : “To God be the Glory!”<br> Hughlon R. Friberg<br> Growing up in a parsonage was a joy, most of the time, for the Friberg Five. Our dad was saved out of a rather rough un-churched background in northeastern Montana, and our mother had been raised in a Pilgrim Holiness family in northern Idaho. They met when the Fribergs moved to Coeur d’Alene and Ray and Hazel attended high school together. Dad was attracted to Mother, her family and their Lord, and was saved soon thereafter. He was also called to pastoral ministry and they began their studies at Northwest Nazarene College upon graduation from high school.<br> I was born soon before they graduated and left Nampa, Idaho, for Dad’s first pastorate. A series of short pastorates in Montana and Wyoming passed and four more Fribergs were added to the family. Being older than the other four and having serious health issues as a child, I grew up nearly an only child. We moved to Washington State when I was in junior high (middle school). But along the way I had been open to God’s work in my life and had repented at five years of age, and felt a call to missions when I was eight or nine, when God spoke to me during a presentation by Louise (Robinson) Chapman, a missionary to Swaziland in Africa.<br> The Seattle area was a great area to be in high school, with involvement in district, zone and local youth events and Youth for Christ, in particular. When Dad felt called to plant a new church in a nearby community, the whole family jumped in to help. These were important formative years for me and my siblings, and three of us are involved in active ministry.<br> Going to Northwest Nazarene College for pre-medical studies came next, because I believed that would be the best way to serve God as a missionary, with my interest in mathematics, science and people. I had no inclination toward pastoral, educational, agricultural, literature or compassionate ministry during those years. College life at NNC was great, and I was very involved in student leadership and activities, including Christian Workers’ Band and the missions club. Evelyn and I met during those years.<br> When the doors to medical school did not open upon graduation from my undergraduate studies, I decided to attend Nazarene Theological Seminary for a year, and then reapply to medical school; but upon beginning my studies in Kansas City and getting married to Evelyn, my understanding of other areas of ministry began to expand. I served for a year in the mid-west in an associate pastoral position, and then we returned to the northwestern United States to pastor for two years, and I was ordained during that time.<br> The call to missions remained strong during those years and in 1971 our application for missionary service was accepted and we were appointed missionaries to Mozambique by the General Board of the Church of the Nazarene. We resigned our church, had our first child, and headed off to Portugal for language study.<br> The next thirty-nine years have gone by in a blur. During our one four-year term in Mozambique, Rev. Armand Doll and I, and a number of other Christian workers and just ordinary folks were arrested and imprisoned for months without charge by the new Communist government. Our second and third children were also born during this time. Evelyn and I were reassigned to the Republic of South Africa, where we served two four-year terms, working in literature development and then pastoral preparation. Following that we served more than twenty years in the Kingdom of Swaziland, continuing in the ministry of pastoral education there. Mobilizing and preparing workers for the harvest is my deep desire.<br> These ministries have put us in contact with many wonderful people in North America and southern Africa, and the training of pastors still beats in my heart as I attempt to fulfill the calling found in my life verse, Matthew 28:16-20, of “making disciples of all nations”, even here in North America. <br> I am enjoying being in Nampa, Idaho, again, where our two daughters and their families live. Our oldest daughter has three young sons, and I am especially enjoying being a part of their lives in these important days. Most of my activities these days have been in getting established on American soil, getting a house, buying a car, and sorting through the jetsam and flotsam of our lives. When I find the time, I want to organize all the stamps I’ve collected, and slides and photos I’ve taken down through the years in all our travels, and maybe even read some of the books I’ve collected!<br>','','$10.00','2013-05-02 07:00:00',NULL,'2013-03-16 21:40:47','2013-03-23 13:25:07','evdb','http://eventful.com/nampa/events/mayors-community-prayer-breakfast-/E0-001-055241779-9?utm_source=apis&utm_medium=apim&utm_campaign=apic','2013-04-10 03:00:23',3,0),('E0-001-055247693-2',1,'V0-001-000139485-3','Authmentis - Abrielway - Cure For The Fall - aaron2013','knittingfactory box office','','','2013-04-05 20:00:00',NULL,'2013-03-17 00:59:11','2013-03-17 00:59:11','evdb','http://eventful.com/boise/events/authmentis-abrielway-cure-fall-aaron2013-/E0-001-055247693-2?utm_source=apis&utm_medium=apim&utm_campaign=apic','2013-04-05 02:58:43',3,0),('E0-001-055249026-0',1,'V0-001-005239086-8','Capital Educators Federal Credit Union Blood Drive','Donation Types: Blood','','','2013-06-18 08:30:00','2013-06-18 12:30:00','2013-03-17 01:52:30','2013-04-07 21:41:20','evdb','http://eventful.com/meridian_id/events/capital-educators-federal-credit-union-blood-dr-/E0-001-055249026-0?utm_source=apis&utm_medium=apim&utm_campaign=apic','2013-04-10 03:01:24',3,0),('E0-001-055249193-1',1,'V0-001-000652989-8','Boise Parks and Recrea